lines.value: is any language widely used beyond the population of its native speakers

lines.value: the de facto status of lingua franca is usually awarded by the masses to the language of the most influential nation(s of the time
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: any given language normally becomes a lingua franca primarily by being used for international commerce but can be accepted in other cultural exchanges especially diplomacy
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: occasionally the term lingua franca is applied to a fully established formal language thus formerly it was said that french was the lingua franca of diplomacy
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: the term lingua franca was originally used by arabs to name all romance languages and especially italian arabs used the name franks for all peoples in western europe
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: then it meant a language with a romance lexicon most words derived from italian and spanish and a very simple grammar that till the end of the 19th century was used by mariners in the mediterranean sea particularly in the middle east and northern africa
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: a related concept is that of a vehicular language it is defined as a basic linguistic structure for proposed international auxiliary languages for example the use of an indo european language or indo european itself in the development of esperanto
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: this is discussed in eco umberto the search for the perfect language blackwell publishers 1995 p 330 ff
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: originally lingua franca referred to a mix of mostly italian with a broad vocabulary drawn from turkish persian french greek and arabic
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: this mixed language pidgin creole language was used for communication throughout the medieval and early modern middle east as a diplomatic language the generic description lingua franca has since become common for any language used by speakers of different languages to communicate with one another
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: italian dialects were spoken in medieval times as lingua franca in the european commercial empires of italian cities genoa venice florence milan pisa siena amalfi and in their colonies located in the middle east and in the mediterranean sea
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: during the renaissance italian was also spoken as language of culture in the main royal courts of europe and among intellectuals
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: the italian language is actually used as a lingua franca in some environments
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: for example in the catholic ecclesiastic hierarchy italian is known by a large part of members and is used in substitution of latin in some official documents as well
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: the presence of italian as the second official language in vatican city indicates not only use in the seat in rome but also in the whole world where an episcopal seat is present
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: during the time of the roman empire the lingua franca was koine greek and latin
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: during the middle ages the lingua franca was greek in the parts of europe and middle east where the byzantine empire held hegemony and latin was primarily used in the rest of europe
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: latin for a significant portion of the expansion of the roman catholic church was used as the basis of the church though this was changed to local languages
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: french was the language of diplomacy in europe from the 17th century until its recent replacement by english and as a result is still the working language of international institutions and is seen on documents ranging from passports to airmail letters
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: for many years until the accession of the united kingdom ireland and denmark in 1973 french and german were the only official working languages of the european economic community
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: french was also the language used among the educated in cosmopolitan cities in north africa such as cairo egypt around the turn of the century until world war ii
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: until the outbreak of the civil war in lebanon french was the language that the upper classes of lebanese society used by way of civilised language
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: french is still a lingua franca in many west african countries where it often enjoys official status a remnant of france's colonial times
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: these african countries together with several other countries throughout the world are members of la francophonie
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: spanish replaced latin as the language of diplomacy and in some aspects culture during the 16th and early 17th centuries when it was replaced by french

lines.value: spanish was also used throughout portions of the former spanish empire particularly in south america
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: today it is a lingua franca in equatorial guinea along with french

lines.value: german served as a lingua franca in large portions of europe during the 19th and 20th centuries in the sciences - particularly in physics chemistry and sociology - as well as in business and politics

lines.value: german was also spoken in much of eastern europe long after the end of world war ii
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: in some academic disciplines most notably philosophy and religious studies a reading knowledge of german is still considered essential and required of doctoral candidates by some universities all over the world not just those in europe

lines.value: although russian language influence has somewhat decreased this popularity polish is still sometimes spoken or at least understood in western border areas of ukraine and belarus
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: english is the current lingua franca of international business and air traffic control and has displaced french as the lingua franca of diplomacy since world war ii
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: it arguably was advanced by the role of english speaking countries in particular the united states in the aftermath of the war
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: the modern trend to use english outside of english speaking countries has a number of sources
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: ultimately the use of english in a variety of locations across the globe is a consequence of the reach of the british empire
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: but the establishment of english as an international lingua franca after world war ii was mostly a result of the spread of english via cultural and technological exports from the united states
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: english is also regarded by some as the global lingua franca owing to the economic hegemony of most of the developed western nations in world financial and business institutions
lines.name: Latin

lines.value: the de facto status of english as the lingua franca in these countries has carried over globally as a result

lines.value: a landmark recognition of the dominance of english in europe came in 1995 when on the accession of austria finland and sweden english joined french and german as one of the working languages of the european union

lines.name: Latin
